The essence of analysis involved the comparison of pieces of data judged to belong to a particular theme, in an effort to recognize the common feature of that theme. Incidents or events were coded (labeled) in terms of as many themes as were relevant and then these incidents or events within the theme compared. The aim was to develop a set of logical themes and associated characteristics (exemplified also by sub themes) which together formed a ‘story’. Ongoing developmental analysis meant that the themes became guides for further analysis of data as the themes in turn were integrated through theorizing. Such a process meant that early themes were often subsumed within this unification of ideas (see
45
).

Consistent with this ethical framework, practical advice already exists. James and colleagues 11 and others 10 offer guidelines for care providers who opt to lie to a resident with dementia. Premised on a person-centred approach these guidelines include ‘taking an individualized approach, agreeing clear definitions about what is considered a lie and using a lie if they are in the best interests of a person’. 10 Complementing these guidelines, recommendations have been made to include:
use of a care plan to ensure consistency (everyone is telling the same lie);
document rationale for the approach;
training and supervision on the potential problems of lying;
education on alternative communicative strategies to use when lying is not appropriate. 3
